05163nam a22007455i 9781503605930DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20202018cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2017046518  a97815036059307 a10.1515/97815036059302doi  a(DE-B1597)563890  a(OCoLC)1178769654  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aPS153.G38bS64 2018 4aPS153.G38b.S64 2018 7aLIT0040302bisacsh04a813/.54098952231 aSohn, Stephen Hong, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aInscrutable Belongings :bQueer Asian North American Fiction /cStephen Hong Sohn. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAsian America00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note on Usage -- tIntroduction: Imagining Queer Asian North American Lives -- t1. Tactical Diversions: Toward Queer Asian North American Formalisms -- t2. Narrative Endurance: Queer Asian North American Storytellers, Survival Plots, and Inscrutable Belongings -- t3. Inscrutable Belongings in Pathology: Infectious Genealogies in Alexander Chee's Edinburgh -- t4. Inscrutable Belongings in Cinema: Filmic Lineages in Noël Alumit's Letters to Montgomery Clift -- t5. Inscrutable Belongings in Hunting: Interracial Surrogacies in Nina Revoyr's Wingshooters -- t6. Inscrutable Belongings in Bondage: Degenerate Descendants in Lydia Kwa's Pulse -- tCoda -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aInscrutable Belongings brings together formalist and contextual modes of critique to consider narrative strategies that emerge in queer Asian North American literature. Stephen Hong Sohn provides extended readings of fictions involving queer Asian North American storytellers, looking to texts including Russell Leong's "Camouflage," Lydia Kwa's Pulse, Alexander Chee's Edinburgh, Nina Revoyr's Wingshooters, and Noël Alumit's Letters to Montgomery Clift. Despite many antagonistic forces, these works' protagonists achieve a revolutionary form of narrative centrality through the defiant act of speaking out, recounting their "survival plots," and enduring to the very last page. These feats are made possible through their construction of alternative social structures Sohn calls "inscrutable belongings." Collectively, the texts that Sohn examines bring to mind foundational struggles for queer Asian North Americans (and other socially marginalized groups) and confront a broad range of issues, including interracial desire, the AIDS/HIV epidemic, transnational mobility, and postcolonial trauma. In these texts, Asian North American queer people are often excluded from normative family structures and must contend with multiple histories of oppression, erasure, and physical violence, involving homophobia, racism, and social death. Sohn's work makes clear that for such writers and their imagined communities, questions of survival, kinship, and narrative development are more than representational-they are directly tied to lived experience.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aAmerican fictionxAsian American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican fictiony21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aAsian Americans in literature. 0aCanadian fictionxAsian authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aCanadian fictiony21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aFamilies in literature. 0aGays in literature. 0aGays' writings, AmericanxHistory and criticism. 0aGays' writings, CanadianxHistory and criticism. 4aAsian American literature. 4aAsian North American literature. 4afamily. 4akinship. 4aliterary criticism. 4anarratology. 4aqueer literature. 4asocial death. 4asoc